> A cherry on top isn't just for sundaes; we're using the fruit to dress savory pork chops in this recipe. You'll be making a pan sauce that features both dried cherries and cherry jam for double the fruity fun. Make sure to get a little of it on the couscous salad—that sweetness is the perfect complement to the tartness of the lemons and tomatoes that are mixed in.

Wash and dry all produce. Bring 2 cups water to a boil in a #small pot{}. Zest and halve @lemon{1}. Halve @grape tomatoes{4%ounce}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, keeping greens and whites separate. Finely chop @parsley{1/4%ounce}.

Place @dried cherries{1%ounce} in a #small bowl{}. Pour over just enough boiling water to cover cherries (you'll need to save 1 cup for the couscous). Set aside.

Put @couscous{1/2%cup} in a #medium bowl{}. Stir in scallion whites and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Pour in 1 cup boiling water and cover. Set aside.

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over high heat. Pat @pork chops{12%ounce} dry with a #paper towel{}. Season all over with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Add to pan and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-6%minutes} per side. Remove from pan and let rest ~{5%minutes}.

Add @chicken stock concentrate{1}, @cherry jam{1%ounce}, and half the cherries along with their steeping water to same pan over medium heat. Give mixture a stir to combine, then bring to a simmer and let bubble until reduced by half.

> TIP: the sauce is ready when it sticks to a spoon.

Season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.

Fluff couscous with a #fork{}. Toss with grape tomatoes, scallion greens, lemon zest, remaining cherries, and juice of half a lemon. Season with @salt{pinch}, @pepper{pinch}, and lemon juice (to taste). Divide couscous between plates and top with pork chops. Drizzle with pan sauce and garnish with parsley.